-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: proof-carrying computation for merge is a textbook NP/P split
--   Generating a correct merge implementation is easy (the algorithm is well-known),
--   but generating a FORMAL PROOF of its correctness is hard — the LLM must
--   identify the right invariants (INV1: sorted prefix is permutation of consumed
--   elements; INV2: last element ≤ next candidates from both lists), construct
--   the sortedness preservation argument (requires case analysis on the comparison
--   branch), and prove termination (i+j increasing, bounded). The crystallized
--   verifier checks all this structurally in constant time per component. The
--   asymmetry is real: the LLM spent most of its effort in frame 4 (proof
--   generation), while the verifier in frame 5 just checked boxes.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: the ⊢∘ gap-filling loop embeds proof repair in the language
--   Unlike program 19 which evolved CODE through test-driven development, this
--   program evolves the PROOF through structure-driven verification. The cycle is:
--   generate proof → verify structure → fill gaps → re-verify. This is exactly
--   how interactive theorem provers work: the prover proposes, the checker
--   identifies holes, the prover fills them. Cell's ⊢∘ combinator captures this
--   pattern as a first-class construct. In this trace, the proof was complete on
--   iteration 1 — but the mechanism for iterative proof repair was ready. A
--   deliberately incomplete proof (missing the permutation argument, say) would
--   trigger fill-gaps to construct Step 3 as a patch.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: the dual proof structure — tests AND formal argument
--   Tests (frame 3) and proof (frame 4) are INDEPENDENT evidence channels.
--   The tests provide empirical confidence: 14 concrete executions covering
--   empty lists, interleaving, duplicates, etc. The proof provides deductive
--   confidence: a logical argument that the algorithm is correct for ALL inputs.
--   Neither subsumes the other. Tests catch implementation bugs the proof might
--   miss (if the proof argues about an idealized version). The proof catches
--   classes of bugs tests might miss (can't test every input). Together they
--   form a proof-carrying computation: code arrives with its own evidence.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: crystallization boundary aligns with computational complexity
--   verify-proof is crystallized (⊢=) because checking proof structure is
--   syntactic pattern matching — does the proof mention "loop-invariant"?
--   Does it reference i, j, result? Does it have a termination argument?
--   These are P-time string/structure checks. generate-proof is soft (∴) because
--   constructing a valid proof requires creative mathematical reasoning — choosing
--   the right invariant, structuring the case analysis, connecting preconditions
--   to the algorithm's correctness. This is the same P/NP boundary that makes
--   all proof-carrying systems work, from PCC in compilers to zero-knowledge proofs.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: generate-code and generate-tests are confluent and independent
--   Frames 1 and 2 evaluated cells from the same ready set. generate-tests does
--   NOT see generate-code's output — it generates tests from the SPEC alone. This
--   independence is crucial: the oracle (tests) doesn't know the implementation
--   strategy, so it can't be biased. Confluence guarantees the same tests whether
